This article is a presidential memorandum from September 21, 2009, regarding the continuation of the national emergency with respect to persons who commit, threaten to commit, or support terrorism. The memorandum states that on September 23, 2001, the President declared a national emergency in response to acts of terrorism, including the September 11, 2001 attacks. The memorandum explains that because the threat of terrorism continues to pose a threat to the United States, the national emergency must continue beyond September 23, 2009. The President is continuing the national emergency for one year, in accordance with the National Emergencies Act. The memorandum will be published in the Federal Register and transmitted to Congress.